<font color="#FF0000">TO TOM</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan  5 15:28:50 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Your letter raises a large number of separate questions, which might require a book-length report to adequately answer.<br>
First, Diem and the American protest movement have little to do with each other.  The protests first started to gain attention in 1967, but not until the Democratic convention in 1968, did they really come to the public attention.  By that time, Diem was already dead for five years, and the war was completely in American hands.<br>
  While I do not want to start defending Diem, it is only fair to say that nobody has ever shown that he supported the French colonialists in any way.  He was one of the many Vietnamese who worked to free Vietnam, but under a non-communist government.  The Buddhist group you mentioned were also working for a non-communist Vietnam ruled by themselves.  In addition, two syncretist religions, the Cao Dai with headquarters in Tay Ninh, and the Hoa Hao in the Mekong Delta, were also striving to rule an independent Vietnam.  Their ambitions may be compared somewhat to the Moslem fundamentalist movements that are seeking to take over some of the countries in the Middle East and North Africa at the present time.  Many other Buddhist groups were present, but they stuck to religion.<br>
   The majority of the rural Vietnamese were neither Buddhist nor Christian but rather anamists.  The culture of Vietnam, like pre-communist China, was fundamentally Confuscist.  Hence, Vietnam was neither a Buddhist nor a Christian culture.<br>
   The rest of the things you reported about Diem sound like they come from the left-wing tracts that were cranked out during and after the war.  These writings, some of which are very convincing, have little or no basis in fact, but they are so often repeated that they are widely believed.  Bernard Fall, probably the best historian of the French war in Indochina, wrote a good deal about Diem.  His party overthrew Emperor Bao Dai, who the French left in power when they were forced to evacuate Indo China.  The conditions in the country at the time were chaotic, with the Saigon police in the hands of Chinese river pirates, for example.  Naturally, he can be accused of all kinds of things without any proof that they really happened the way they were described.<br>
   The tracts about the Vietnam War, written mainly by academics at American universities who have no first hand knowledge at all, include some of the most irritating lies I have ever read.  These fall into a general pattern, because the communists have redefined the concepts of truth and lie. I can provide a few examples that you might want to consider.<br>
In 1972, I spent a short time in New York.  Tales of how American B-52s had bombed a hospital in North Vietnam induced some well meaning suburbanites to set up a stall in a shopping center to collect money to send to North Vietnam to rebuild the hospital.  The whole show was televised, with gory pictures supplied by the North Vietnamese.  About a year later, a Swiss friend who was also a friend of a Swiss representative of the International Red Cross stationed in Hanoi at the time, told me that the bombings had been precisely accurate.  The main railroad station and freight yards had been thoroughly destroyed, while the buildings across the street had been undamaged.  His friend, as a Red Cross representative, knew where every hospital in Hanoi was located, and he said that not a single one of them had suffered any damage at all.  The whole thing was a sham!<br>
   This kind of thing has a long tradition.  A friend in Hong Kong told me that he was convinced that the United States used biological weapons in Korea because of a film shown in all Hong Kong movie theaters during the 1950s.  I later saw the film myself.  It showed an American pilot with tears in his eyes apologizing for dropping germ bombs on all the women and children in North Korea.  Did the United States use biological warfare in Korea?  Do you believe it or not?  I do know that there were Americans who would have made such a film for an extra package of cigarettes, knowing that nothing would happen to them when they came home.  It has also been suggested that some of the American POWs were not released after both the Korean and Vietnam Wars because they stubbornly refused to cooperate with the communists.  What do you believe?<br>
   Recently, Cuban news films, broadcast in Europe, have reported that many crops in Cuba began to die after unidentified aircraft, presumably from the United States, dropped something over their fields.  It is claimed that bacteria or viruses are now being used to kill Cuban crops. Do you believe this?<br>
   While I have no inside information about any of these stories, I personally spoke with doctors who had worked in the hospital in Hué.  One patient was recovering from brain surgery, which had been performed on board an American ship in 1968.  When the communists captured the city during the Tet offensive, they put a bullet through this patient´s head because the Americans had operated on him.  They also shot most of the other patients, as well.  The Khmer Rough also shot all of the patients in the hospital at Kampong Cham while they were unsuccessfully trying to capture the city in 1973.  I personally knew a family in Hué whose two sons were taken away by the fleeing communist forces after the Tet offensive.  First, they looked through all the bodies in a mass grave containing the remains of about 800 teenage boy from the city without finding their sons.  Several weeks later, another grave was found containing about 700 bodies, and there they found the remains of their two sons.  All together, about 3000 civilians from Hué were massacred systematically and deliberately by the North Vietnamese who had the city for about three weeks.  I know this personally, not from the American press.  In contrast to the killing of about 80 civilians at My Lai, nobody was ever put on trial or punished for these mass murders or any of the others that took place in other parts of the country at the hands of the North Vietnamese.<br>
   With regard to saving Dien Bien Phu, tactical nuclear weapons were only one of the options discussed.  Very likely, B-29s from Guam would have dropped conventional bombs on the Viet Minh artillery positions.  The number of bombs required would have been negligible compared to the numbers dropped in the American war a decade later.  According to Bernard Fall, the American most responsible for having kept the bombers from flying was the Congressional representative at the meeting, Lyndon Johnson.<br>
   The view of the French war is somewhat simplistic in view of the fact that the world had changed considerably during the eight years the war was in progress.  In 1945, the French were permitted by Truman to recapture their former colony by force to please de Gaulle, who was regarded as the only man who could keep the communists from taking over the French government.  Shortly later, de Gaulle grew tired of the whole thing and quit, leaving the French to be ruled by governments that seldom lasted more than a few months.  The landing of the French was brutal, and they gained a good deal of hatred by their shelling of civilians in Haiphong. The return of the French played little role in the balance of power in the Far East in 1946.  China was safely in the hands of the Kuomintang, Stalin was still Uncle Joe, and the Cold War had not yet begun.<br>
In 1954, the entire world situation was different.  The Berlin Blockade had started the Cold War, China was ruled by Mao Tse Tung, the British were fighting a communist insurgency in Malaya, and America had just achieved a stalemate in Korea.  Stalin and Mao were apparently good friends and willing to work together to achieve a world communist empire by force.<br>
The French were trying to find a way out of their colonial war in Indo China because of all the blood and treasure it was costing.  However, the United States, which was paying for the war, insisted that it was their moral duty to humanity to do their part to stop the offensive of totalitarian communism.  According to Bernard Fall, the French were asking to quit.  If it was a colonial war, it should be stopped because colonies should bring profits, not losses.  If it was a crucade, then was it not the duty of the United States, Great Britain, and the rest of the Free World to help them with the air power that they lacked?<br>
Bernard Fall also reported that General Giap lost about 40% of the entire Viet Minh while capturing Dien Bien Phu.  Because he won, he gained tremendous prestige and could force the French to leave Indo China.  If he had not captured the position, he would no longer have had the strength to operate effectively against the French in the Red River Delta.  At the time, the United States could have put the communists out of action at little cost.<br>
Would that have returned Vietnam to the French colonial empire?  At the time, France had already formed the so-called French Union, under which Vietnam, Laos, and Cambodia were becoming independent countries with ties to France somewhat like the members of the British Commonwealth have with England.  The French knew already that they could not keep control of the region as colonies, but they wanted to leave the countries under the control of non-communist governments.  Hence, what started as a colonial war in 1945 and 1946 had completely changed its complexion by 1954.  With the rapid forcible takeover of countries by the communists around the world during the 1950s together with the expected declarations of independence by all of the former European colonies, which the United States supported, it is not hard to understand that many American political leaders feared that a monolithic communist power would jump into the vacuum and create a vast empire throughout much of the world using subversion and terrorism?  Vietnam was a natural place to stop the advancing communism because in that country, there was a strong communist party seeking to suppress a very strong anti-communist resistance, which, unfortunately, was divided against itself, with several Buddhist and syncretist sects and various secular political parties competing against one another for leadership of the anti-communist front.<br>
   I though that my last statement was clear.  I will explain it in a separate message to follow.<br>
    <br><br>

